the people with a traditional way of life in the Hunter region. The complication 
rate was 11%. The extension and pathology of the cholesteatomas indicated late 
and infrequent contact with an ENT specialist. The follow-up study revealed 53% 
dry ears with intact tympanic membrane, and 47% with intermittent ear discharge. 
Residual or recurrent cholesteatoma was found in 46% of the patients, less 
frequently when the primary operation included mastoidectomy with canal 
wall-down technique. We recommend this operation in most Greenlandic Inuit with 
cholesteatomas.

